# Billboards & Signs: Design for the Blink of an Eye

A billboard has about 3 seconds of attention from a driver going 60 mph. A sign at the end of a hallway is read from 20 meters away. These aren’t just “bigger UI”, they follow completely different rules about what information even belongs, and how it should be sized. Let’s make your message readable at warp speed.

## The Distance Rule

Here's the fundamental constraint: type legibility depends on size.

Rough guide: **1 inch of letter height ≈ 100 feet of readable distance** (in good conditions).

This means:
- A 4" headline reads from ~400 feet
- A 0.5" body text on the same sign is invisible beyond 50 feet
- A 1-inch pixel at 10 feet is fine. At 200 feet it blurs.

## Implications

- **Reduce to one message.** A billboard has 3 seconds and 7 words maximum. Headline and maybe a URL.
- **Heavy typeface only.** Light fonts disappear at distance. Use black or extrabold weights.
- **Extreme contrast.** The 4.5:1 ratio is for close-up screens. Outdoor signage needs 7:1 minimum. Black on white or white on black.
- **No decorative type.** The pretty display font in your logo often fails at distance. Use condensed grotesques like Helvetica Condensed.

## Scale by Distance

| Distance    | Min Type Height | Weight          |
|-------------|-----------------|-----------------|
| 3m (indoor) | 48pt            | Bold            |
| 10m         | 150pt           | Extrabold       |
| 50m         | 300pt           | Black/Condensed |
| 100m        | 600pt+          | Black only      |

## Rules

- Never put body text on outdoor signage. If you can't say it in 7 words, don't.
- Use heavy, condensed, or black-weight fonts. Not regular or light.
- High-contrast pairs only: black/white, black/yellow, white/dark blue.
- Test at actual distance before printing. What looks fine on screen fails at 30 meters.
- For digital signs: text must be visible mid-scroll.

